reviewText: While I was never a fan of WCW, I bought some old VHS tapes because I was so sick of watching the some old crap in WWE. Here is my thoughts on Starcade 98Rey Misterio Jr. VS Juventud Guerrera VS Kidman: Match of the night; These three wrestlers gelled well togehter. I cant believe this match was left off Misterio's dvd set. WWE is releasing The Best of Starcade on dvd soon (I hope) and this match better be included.Note: Alot of matches in WCW at this time had outside interference. Some matches it hurts but some it doesnt.Eddie Guerrero VS Billy Kidman: Kidman wanted this match, so he got it. Kidman was getting a huge push at the time. A good match with lots of outside interference.Konnan VS Jericho: Never liked Konnan. This match was alright but nothing to speical.Brian Adams and Scott Norton VS Fit Finaly and Jerry Flynn: I always enjoyed Adams in the ring, god rest his soul. A very good match but Norton sucks in the ring. Apparently he is big in Japan though.Norman Smiley VS Prince Iaukea: With all the talent WCW had and we get this match? Well it wasnt half bad, even though no one cared.Perry Saturn VS The Cat: Always liked Saturn; This match was decent but nothing speical. Why was the Cat so popular anyways? Because he danced? Whoopty do!Eric Bishoff VS Ric Flair: This matches were a dime a dozen back in the last years of WCW. The outcome would be forgotten in a matter of days.DDP VS Giant: I was excited to see this match. Despite Hart coming out, the match went really well. I loved the ending.Goldberg VS Nash: If you think Goldberg was 173-0, then you believe in Santa. Nash was a booker in the company at the time and hogged the spotlight. Can you guess who won? Nash put on a good match.Overall, there were some very good matches on this card. Id recommend it to fans who miss the days of the WWE-WCW wars. As I said, WWE is planning on releasing Best of Starcade this summer. Cant wait for that.

reviewText: Starrcade 98" one of the most remembered, but ultimately controversial and somewhat hated ppvs. Man what was WCW thinking? Allow me to explain.Bill Goldberg went 170 I believe and was the first UNDEFEATED man in wrestling history to first gain the WCW/NWA US Title from Raven following a victory at Spring Stampede 98 over Perry Saturn.He then earned a title shot in WCW Nitro after beating Scott Hall and then faced Hollywood Hogan in what really was a no contest to become the first undefeated man to win the WCW WORLD TITLE!!! WCW for almost a full year rode the Golberg bandwagon and it worked, they were dominating the ratings and dominating the WWF, all of a sudden someone got the stupid idea to end it all here at Starrcade 98. Who was it? Eric Bishoff or was it the politics of WCW front office like the WWF to screw its wrestlers after the company profited of them? Maybe.Well here are the matches, they were actually all excellent don't let that low rating here on IMDb fool you, I am guessing that low rating comes from what I just said about the Goldberg match.WCW Cruiserweight Title match.Rey Misterio Jr. vs. Juventud Guerrera vs. Kidman.Great match, this was when WCW still had a great Latino audience and the cruiserweights were a example of luchador wrestling. 10 out 10 for this match and as added bonus Eddie Guerrero challenges the winner, so we get a bonus match.Konnan vs. Jericho for TV title. This was or should is when Jericho shoots his mouth on the ring. A good match, semi interesting.Brian Adams +Scott Norton vs. Jerry Flynn + Fit Finlay. Eh somewhat interesting match involving the NWO, the ending was never in doubt. Scott Norton look like he used enough steroids toknock of bear.Norman Smiley vs. Prince Iaukea. Eh probably the only lame match on the ppv.Perry Saturn vs. The Cat. This was good. The Cat comes out and tries to intimidate Saturn by saying "The Cat" is gonna whoop his ass, but looking at physiques its obvious Saturn had a big edge. Ending is pretty obvious.Eric Bishoff vs. Ric Flar. Whooo!! Well here we have a rare match with Bishoff when he was still running the NWO. After several humiliating incidents with Bishoff, embarrassing referees and Flair's family it came down to this. Good match. Flair beats up Eric, who has no wrestling body at all. Hes a weakling. However the NWO comes to bail him and well you can guess how it ends.Diamond Dallas Page vs. The Giant. This comes of the heels of a rivalry between Page and Bret Hart, who together with the Giant, gave Page a serious beating, culminating with Page being chokeslam of a podium.Hart makes a surprise appearance in the match. Good match.Now the main event Golberg (Champ) vs. Kevin Nash.Well after beating the heck out of Scott Hall this was Goldberg attempt to knock the other Outsider. Both men prove their equals, but its obvious Goldberg, wrestling and strenght wise, outmatch Nash.(SPOILERS) Enter Bam Bam Bigelow trying to interfere in the match, but gets rewarded with a spear from Goldberg. Then Scott Hall the coward he is, comes in dressed as a security person and shocks Golderg with a tazer. Nash takes advantages and steals the title from Goldberg. A really cheap victory, probably the cheapest of Nash's career and this ends the Goldberg run for WCW, which again was the dumbest move WCW made.It's like when the WWF rode Bret Hart after Hogan left and then screwing Bret Hart who went to WCW and revived the ratings there.After this, WCW started to go a bit downhill, they eventually came back up and title changed hands, but this hurt WCW though, I am sure Bishoff and company would have liked to changed the outcome looking back but it still lucky for them wasn't the end for WCW not until 2001
summary: Decent ppv plagued by a horrible finish.

reviewText: Another event that I was able to catch on WWE Classics On Demand in the WCW's biggest event of the year in Starrcade 1998. The hype surrounding this event was all about one thing & that was the main event in WCW Champion Goldberg would put his title & his undefeated record of 173-0 at the time against what was being called his toughest challenge to date & winner of the World War 3 battle royal a month prior in Kevin Nash. And for those wondering, even though Chris Benoit was not on the card, his name & face was removed in the early opening shot when speaking about the Horsemen. Speaking of the Horsemen, the leader of the group in Ric Flair returned to Starrcade to get a match that he has been waiting for quite some time against Eric Bischoff.WCW Cruiserweight Champion Billy Kidman vs Rey Mysterio vs Juventud Guerrera. This match was a spinoff the previous Kidman/Juventud feud with Mysterio being added to the mix due to the whole LWO storyline going on at the time. Kidman & Mysterio showed some future foreshadowing in which they decided to work as team partners & attack Juventud since both men had issues with him before the "every man for himself" rule came back into effect. This was the match of the night for me as this match was a rare gem for WCW cruiserweight action as it was just high impact & fast paced throughout with each man building momentum before another one was able to take advantage along with the storytelling of how Rey's injured knee was worked on at the time but the biggest issue was the appearance of the LWO leader in Eddie Guerrero that was so disgusted in the outcome that he challenged the winner leading to...WCW Cruiserweight Champion Billy Kidman vs Eddie Guerrero. This match in which Eddie wrestled in his street clothes. The storytelling was on point as Eddie attempted to ground Kidman for most of the match due to Kidman just wrestling a long match just a few minutes prior while Juventud & Mysterio were at ringside to provide help to the person that they wanted to win. This went back & forth into a good match between these two that only continued this fued that was cut short to Guerrero's car accident not to long after this but did its job in showcasing Kidman as a fighting champion.Norman Smiley vs Prince Iaukea. This was just a last minute filler match that was added to the card & nothing really memorable or special here as Smiley was nothing more than a comedy act.Perry Saturn vs Ernest Miller. Just an average match that had it's moments but again, nothing to get too excited about which is a shame considering how Saturn was really on fire at this time in WCW.Brian Adams & Scott Norton vs Fit Finlay & Jerry Flynn. Even though Finlay tried to make this match watchable, this was a long & boring match between these two that again was nothing memorable once it was over.WCW Television Chmapion Konnan vs Chris Jericho. Even Konnan was the champion, Jericho came out with the championship belt as he felt he never lost the title to begin with. Jericho used his high-flying offense early before Konnan took advantage of Jericho's arrogance that got Jericho to not only start acting serious but also desperate before Konnan was able to win the match & reclaim the actual belt. This was a good average match as Jericho brought more out of Konnan than usual at this time.Ric Flair vs Eric Bischoff. As it was mentioned earlier in the show that Bischoff made sure that Flair came to this match alone so the Horsemen were banned from the arena. Flair came out with one thing on his mind & that was to beat the hell out of Bischoff which is what he did for the most part with Bischoff only getting in heel tactics such as low blows, a foreign object that ended up busting Flair open & hitting the referee but it was the appearance of a former Horsemen member & someone Flair has a history that brought an outcome that left everyone from the announcers to the audience shocked in the result.Diamond Dallas Page vs The Giant. DDP wanted revenge for the Giant costing him the United States title a few weeks back on Nitro including a chokeslam off the stage so due to that, this match was made a No Disqualification match. Page brought the fight to the Giant throughout but the Giant showed that he had the power advantage by constantly using his size to get the offense & even used power moves such as a bear hug to wear DDP out. Bret Hart would make a cameo in this match with a chair before DDP provided a unique counter of the Diamond Cutter to win this good match that was better than their WWF matches a few years later.WCW Champion Goldberg vs Kevin Nash. Once again, this match was also given the No Disqualification stipulation as it was not only Goldberg's title that was on the line but also his perfect undefeated record of 173-0. Both men came out aggressive & even used a series of submission holds (not a typo, Nash was doing submission holds) before developing into a back & forth power match with each man continually exchanging offense. However the match took a huge turn with the appearance of Disco Inferno (WTF?), Bam Bam Bigelow but more importantly the appearance of Scott Hall with a taser gun in a security outfit that brought an end to the reign of Goldberg. Other than how the ending was played out, this was a nice main event that was better than anyone else thought it was going to be.Overall, the only matches worth checking out on this card were the two Cruiserweight title matches along with the main event which has been released on the Starrcade DVD already so this is an event that if you can find real cheap & used, then I recommend but other than that, look for the opener online & find the main event on another DVD set because the rest was forgettable.

reviewText: The best matches were the Cruiserweight title matches which both were high-flying showstealers. The Ric Flair-Eric Bischoff match was a one-sided but still entertaining brawl. The Kevin Nash-Goldberg-World title match was a dud and the only the only that fans are going to remember about this bout is that it was Goldberg's first loss ever in WCW. You can call it a good idea becuase no one can be undefeated forever or a bad idea becuase Goldberg could been great for Starrcade like Hulk Hogan was for Wrestlemania. I have no comment on the loss. The rest were pretty good. I give this PPV a 6 out of 10.

A few matches are good like the first few, with kidman wrestling twice but the rest of the matches are pretty weak, all I have to say is Fit Finely, who's booking this, oh thats right it was Kevin Nash back then, which brings us to the main event.  What a suprise Nash takes the belt from Goldberg, officially starting the downward spiral in Goldberg's career.  Worse yet is Nash's effort "his" big match, its like he's on no-dose.  Common Nash show some pride in your work.  What a lousy video, if you want WCW in its prime form, get the 98 Halloween Havoc, at least DDP has testicular fortitude even if he's 46.
